<TEXT>
cardinal john oconnor on thursday warned that 
roman catholic officials who support abortion rights could face 
excommunication but church experts and politicians dismissed the 
threat 
the cardinal delivered his strongest and clearest statement yet 
on the subject of excommunicating prochoice catholic politicians 
in a 12page piece in catholic new york the weekly archdiocesan 
newspaper 
where catholics are perceived not only as treating church 
teaching on abortion with contempt but helping to multiply 
abortions by advocating legislation supporting abortion or by 
making public funds available for abortion bishops may decide that 
such catholics must be warned that they are at risk of 
excommunication wrote oconnor who is the chairman of the 
bishops committee for prolife activities 
if such actions persist bishops may consider excommunication 
the only option he added oconnor did not mention any 
politicians by name and said any bishop would engage in 
considerable prayer and discussion before taking such action 
excommunication blocks a catholic from receiving most sacraments 
within the church 
us rep charles rangel who was barred from speaking at a high 
school graduation at st patricks cathedral last week because of 
his prochoice stance said he did not want to believe oconnor had 
issued such a meanspirited statement 
the cardinal obviously has a closer working relationship with 
god than i do so therefore i would not risk challenging his 
authority rangel dny said in washington on the other 
hand i feel very comfortable that comes judgment day we will be 
on equal footing 
gov mario cuomo speaking at city hall reaffirmed his position 
of personal opposition to abortion but public support of a womans 
right to decide the governor then acknowledged the talk of 
excommunication bothered him 
i dont like to hear it how could you this is something 
fundamental to our family said cuomo 
experts in church policy disagreed with oconnor saying support 
of a prochoice stance was not grounds to expel politicians from 
the church 
hes wrong said the rev richard mcbrien chairman of the 
theology department at the university of notre dame in south bend 
ind on the question of abortion the only person clearly 
subjected to excommunication would be the person who procures the 
abortion 
that would mean the woman and perhaps her doctor but not 
politicians he said 
mario cuomo is not performing abortions mario cuomo is not 
running an abortion clinic on the side said mcbrien he 
oconnor doesnt really have a canonical leg to stand on 
the rev robert drinan a former massachusetts congressman 
agreed that oconnors statements were misguided 
that goes against what the bishops have been saying said 
drinan a georgetown university law center professor i think 
that wont be taken that seriously catholics and everyone else 
would resent it 
but the rev joseph penna speaking for the archdiocese of new 
york said thursday evening that a person could be excommunicated 
even if they do not directly take part in an abortion 
it goes beyond who procures an abortion said penna of st 
josephs seminary in yonkers if church officials determined that 
an individual served as an accomplice to an abortion by giving 
scandal to other people that person could be excommunicated he 
said 
and by giving scandal i mean a person would look at someone 
else and say if that person can do it so can i said penna 
speaking of the leadership roles that politicians play in society 
