<TEXT>
explosions ripped through a gasoline 
storage plant in southwest indiana on wednesday seriously injuring 
three men 
the largest of seven cylindrical tanks at the greene county farm 
bureau coop exploded about 230 pm and was still burning 
wednesday night state police cpl omar davis said in bloomington 
davis said officials of the us environmental protection agency 
were determining whether to smother the blaze with foam or let it 
burn itself out 
although fears that the fire would spread to the other tanks 
subsided residents up to two miles away were evacuated 
two businesses are very close and there are a few scattered 
homes nearby but its mostly rural said sheriffs dispatcher 
sheri campbell 
the size of the tank and the amount of gasoline it held had not 
been determined davis said noting conflicting reports that it 
contained 8000 gallons or 42000 gallons 
davis said the accident occurred as workers emptied a gasoline 
truck into the tank using a pump 
the pump apparently sparked and ignited the truck and from 
there somehow or other the tank caught fire he said 
the three injured were taken to hospitals to be treated for 
burns 
leo goodwin listed in critical condition was taken to riley 
hospital in indianapolis dick smiley also listed as critical was 
taken to wishard hospital in indianapolis and richard knight who 
was in serious condition was taken to deaconess hospital in 
evansville davis said their ages and hometowns were unavailable 
dark smoke was seen as far away as six or seven miles from the 
plant which is outside switz city 75 miles southwest of 
indianapolis 
