<TEXT>
the kgb has identified a park outside the 
ukrainian city of kharkov as the likely burial site of 3900 polish 
officers massacred by the soviet secret police in 1940 the polish 
pap news agency reported 
the victims represent part of the approximately 15000 polish 
officers from three internment camps who were systematically killed 
in what has become known as the katyn massacre 
more than 4300 bodies of the executed polish officers were 
discovered at katyn near smolensk in 1943 but the exact fate of 
the other missing officers has remained a mystery the 15000 
officers were seized by the soviet union in the early days of world 
war ii 
soviet officials acknowledged in april that the officers were 
killed by the nkvd stalins secret police and the kgbs 
predecessor for decades soviet governments had maintained that 
the officers died at the hands of invading german armies 
pap quoted the chief of the kgb office in kharkov a city of 12 
million 500 miles south of moscow as saying the polish soldiers 
were buried in a wooded park around the city the kgb chief was not 
identified the report was published wednesday in the polish 
government newspaper rzeczpospolita 
pap said the burial site also contained some soviet victims of 
the nkvd 
the officers whose remains were found at katyn had been interned 
at a camp in kozielsk in western russia 
still unknown is the final resting place of the more than 6000 
polish officers interned at the third soviet camp at ostashkov a 
town 200 miles northwest of moscow 
