massachusetts democrats have filed a lawsuit 
accusing a white house aide and the springfield police union of 
conspiring to disrupt the partys convention 
the union picketed the convention hall in springfield on june 2 
preventing delegates from entering for several hours 
among those named in the lawsuit filed in state court wednesday 
were ronald kaufman deputy assistant to president bush for 
personnel and union president robert jacobson 
the lawsuit alleges that kaufman and the union conspired to 
violate democratic delegates right to assemble and that pickets 
struck shoved and spit on people who tried to enter the convention 
hall 
kaufman was in springfield at the time of the convention spoke 
with jacobson the night before the protest and also met with 
members of the union in washington before the convention 
but he and jacobson have repeatedly denied they conspired to 
interfere with the convention jacobson said the protest was part 
of a dispute with the city 
im glad theyre filing because ive got a secret weapon 
truth kaufman said wednesday 
the lawsuit seeks an unspecified amount in damages 
