<TEXT>
slight genetic mutations allowed a monkey aids 
virus to kill within days rather than months a finding that could 
improve scientists understanding of human aids researchers 
reported today 
the result raises the possibility that a human aids strain may 
exist that kills within days or weeks of infection rather than 
years said study coauthor patricia fultz 
a federal aids expert said he strongly doubts such a human 
strain exists but he and fultz said the monkey virus may still 
help scientists study aids 
the new work is presented in the british journal nature by 
fultz of the yerkes regional primate research center at emory 
university in atlanta with scientists there at harvard university 
and the stanford university school of medicine 
they studied a recently isolated strain of a simian 
immunodeficiency virus scientists study these monkey viruses 
called sivs to gain clues about aids 
in monkeys called pigtailed macaques the fastacting siv 
produced bloody diarrhea and death in as little as six days after 
it infected the animal researchers reported in contrast the 
virus from which this strain evolved allows eight months or more of 
survival after infection fultz said wednesday 
the genetic makeup of the fastacting virus strongly resembles 
that of other sivs and gained its wallop by acquiring only subtle 
mutations so the possibility that a fastacting human aids virus 
exists must be considered the researchers said 
but malcolm martin of the laboratory of molecular biology at the 
national institute of allergy and infectious diseases in bethesda 
md said it is highly unlikely such a virus exists 
no such virus has been observed in the hundreds of thousands of 
people infected with the aids virus and if a fastacting human 
version were going to appear it would have shown up by now he 
said 
further study of the fastacting siv strain may identify the 
genes that make it act so quickly which in turn may give clues for 
fighting the human aids virus fultz said 
martin said that since the virus causes severe disease more 
quickly than other sivs it may also provide a way to test aids 
therapies more quickly 
</TEXT>
