a gasoline barge sprang a leak wednesday night 
spilling at least 1200 gallons and prompting officials to close 
two busy waterways that have been plagued by spills authorities 
said 
the source of the spill into the arthur kill waterway was 
believed to be a tank on the barge holding more than 222000 
gallons of unleaded gas said coast guard petty officer don burt 
the tank was emptied about two hours after the leak was reported 
to the coast guard at 805 pm but officials were waiting for 
divers to confirm no other tanks were leaking into the arthur kill 
waterway dividing new yorks staten island and new jersey 
it was not immediately known what caused the spill more than 10 
million gallons of fuel were loaded into 10 tanks on the barge at 
carteret nj during the afternoon then the vessel traveled 
across the arthur kill to a mobil corp operation on staten island 
after the spill the fire department sent about 10 units to the 
port mobil section of staten island spokesman john mulligan said 
the arthur kill and adjacent kill van kull were closed shortly 
after 9 pm as a safety precaution while firefighters attempted to 
disperse the gasoline to speed evaporation 
brooks said it was not immediately known how long the kills 
would remain closed booms were laid at entrances to nearby creeks 
to prevent the gasoline from spreading inland he said 
he said the barge was owned by bouchard transportation of new 
york calls to the company were not answered wednesday night 
the amount of oil accidentally released into the two kills this 
year is four times as much as was reported in all of 1989 
the most recent accident occurred last week when an 811foot 
tanker leaked 260000 gallons of oil into the kill van kull on 
jan 2 a pipe from an exxon refinery leaked more than 567000 
gallons of oil into the arthur kill 
