<TEXT>
researchers have created a wand that 
alters living animal cells by bombarding them with microscopic 
dnacoated pellets duke university scientists said wednesday 
there is a whole range of genetic applications said stephen 
johnston a molecular biologist at duke 
i think we are just at the frontier of realizing what the 
potentials are of being able to modify cells in the living 
organism he said 
the scientists say the technology could be ready for use within 
a year and eventually could help treat liver and heart diseases 
but they added that its future depends on further breakthroughs 
and on societys attitude toward genetic engineering 
the research results were reported wednesday at the annual 
meeting of the tissue culture association in houston 
duke researchers in collaboration with scientists at cornell 
university and the dupont co used the wand to alter cells of 
living mice by injecting new genes with little or no adverse 
effects they said 
the wand eventually may be used to treat some liver diseases 
by supplying the missing gene that causes certain defects to alter 
pancreatic cells to produce insulin or to alter muscle cells to 
treat heart diseases the scientists said 
its an interesting new approach to a very important problem 
in modern molecular biology said lee hood professor of biology 
at california institute of technology 
using pressurized helium gas the wand propels at 1000 
feet a second microscopic dnacoated pellets into the tissue 
about 10 million pellets each containing about 30 genes are 
introduced the pellets are so small 00003 inches across that 
they do not cause extensive damage researchers said 
dna or deoxyribonucleic acid is the collection of genes in 
living cells that determine individual characteristics 
because the pellets do not penetrate deep into the tissue the 
animal does not suffer any trauma or skin irritation johnston 
said adding that a human subject might feel a slight stinging 
sensation 
the wand must be improved before it can be applied to human 
diseases researchers said they said questions remain about 
whether the altered genes can permanently take hold in animal cells 
to date the genes have been effective only as long as the 
pellets remained in the tissue about 10 days in the ear of a mouse 
existing techniques for modifying the dna of living organisms 
such as bonemarrow transplants involve an indirect process in 
which cells are removed from the patient altered and then 
reintroduced the researchers said 
dupont said it will make a version of the wand available to 
researchers 
the precursor to the wand is a mechanism that uses gunpowder 
to fire genecoated tungsten pellets into plant cells the 
researchers said that instrument was invented by john sanford of 
cornell university who also worked on the wand team 
dupont bought the rights to the earlier instrument and markets 
it to agriculture and industry 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

