<TEXT>
the agency that put men on the moon rescued 
lost satellites and sent spacecraft to distant planets is looking 
for new worlds to conquer and it wants ideas from you 
the national aeronautics and space administration decided 
recently to go outside the agency away from its normal 
contractors to get fresh thinking on ways to establish a permanent 
base on the moon and put humans on mars 
not only the public but universities engineering schools and 
professional science and engineering organizations were invited to 
contribute 
nasa even set up a tollfree telephone line for the ideas 
8006777796 
nasa administrator richard h truly has sent more than 3200 
letters to the heads of schools asking for their help the rand 
corp in santa monica calif will filter the good ideas from the 
bad before passing them on to washington the tollfree number 
reaches rand 
the search for ideas from an agency noted for turning science 
fiction into reality started last july with a pledge by president 
bush that the united states was headed back to the moon this 
time to stay and would push on to mars 
bush set that goal in a speech observing the 20th anniversary of 
mans first footsteps on the moon more recently he said the mars 
landing should be accomplished by the 50th anniversary of the neil 
armstrongbuzz aldrin moon landing in the year 2019 
a nasasponsored study estimated the cost of going to mars at 
500 billion or more a sum that would require more money each year 
than the agencys current budget for all space activities 
vice president dan quayle as head of the national space 
council has been pressing nasa officials to go outside normal 
channels and cast their net widely for more efficient and 
cheaper ways to return to the moon and to plant the us flag on 
mars 
the space agency also has been challenged by others such as 
lawrence livermore national laboratory which said astronauts could 
be landed on mars for 11 billion using existing rockets and 
inflatable spacecraft and the aerospace industries association has 
urged that a study group be set up outside of nasa to receive 
proposals and evaluate them 
in answer to such unaccustomed outside pressure truly announced 
his agency was organizing a formal searchforideas program called 
