<TEXT>
five researchers have been inducted into the 
agriculture departments science hall of fame 
the five were recognized this week by the agricultural research 
service the departments chief scientific agency to be eligible 
for the hall of fame scientists must either be retired or eligible 
to retire and to have gained recognitions by national and 
international colleagues for their work 
r dean plowman administrator of the agency said the 
achievements of the five are worthy of being emulated by younger 
agricultural scientists 
the five new inductees included 
retired biologist theodore c byerly who died may 17 for his 
investigations of how nutrition genetics and the environment 
affect the hatching of chicken eggs his findings helped boost the 
hatching rate to 85 percent from 65 percent 
his studies were based at the agencys beltsville md research 
center until 1963 when he left for a series of highlevel usda 
administrative posts 
retired geneticist gordon e dickerson who was responsible for 
developing major concepts and methods to genetically improve 
productivity in cattle sheep swine and poultry 
before retiring in 1987 dickerson worked at the roman l hruska 
meat animal research center in clay center neb 
chemist robert w holley who won the 1968 nobel prize in 
physiology and medicine he discovered the class of ribonucleic 
acids now known as transfer rna one of the essential building 
blocks in the bodys instruction system for the production of 
protein 
holleys work for the agency was based at the plant soil and 
nutrition laboratory in ithaca ny he is now with the salk 
institute in san diego 
wheat researcher virgil a johnson codeveloper of 28 improved 
wheat varieties that have set new standards of productivity for 
hard red winter wheat varieties that he worked on have at times 
made up as much as 25 percent of the total us wheat acreage 
before retiring in 1986 johnson worked at the agencys wheat 
research unit in lincoln neb 
corn researcher george f sprague whose integration of 
theoretical quantitative genetics and applied plant breeding led 
him to develop methods that have resulted in the production of 
superior corn hybrids 
sprague was leader of the corn and sorghum investigations 
laboratory at the beltsville center before he retired in 1973 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
public comment is being sought on an 
agriculture department proposal to allow salty whey to be covered 
by federal whey standards 
salty whey is the moisture removed from cheese curd through a 
salting process the standards would apply to whey after the salt 
is removed 
daniel d haley administrator of the departments agricultural 
marketing service said wednesday that current rules allow us 
grading only on whey that originates as saltless 
at present salty whey represents a small amount of the total 
whey that results from cheesemaking and is discarded because it is 
so salty he said but new technology can economically remove the 
salt from salted whey 
dried and condensed whey are significant sources of vitamins and 
protein for humans and are used to some extent in animal feed 
haley said 
comments on the proposal can be sent by aug 13 to director 
dairy division ams usda room 2968s po box 96456 washington 
dc 200906456 copies of the proposal are available from that 
office or telephone 2024474392 
