<TEXT>
secretary of state james a baker iii wants to 
discuss elements of a final settlement of world war ii at a major 
meeting in berlin june 22 a state department official says 
baker will meet with soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze 
and their counterparts from france britain and east and west 
germany 
raymond gh seitz assistant secretary for european affairs 
said at a house foreign affairs subcommittee hearing wednesday that 
baker will not present a draft treaty 
he said possible topics include the principles that will guide 
the resolution of the borders issue of germany part of that 
affects the polish question of course 
and secondly there will be an effort to at least have a 
discussion of the elements that would make up a final settlement 
poland is eager to have a reaffirmation of germanys present 
eastern border to forestall any future claim by a united germany of 
territory that is now polish 
seitz said the united states wants to terminate the rights of 
the four victors of world war ii over germany such as their 
occupation of berlin 
that would be part of the final settlement he added 
our belief is that the victors rights ought to be 
terminated as quickly as possible and probably at the time of 
german unification he said 
the united states would then recognize the unification though it 
may not be legally necessary he said explaining that was because 
the united states already recognizes west germany as the successor 
state to adolf hitlers third reich which included both east and 
west germany 
earlier in the day baker outlined to the full foreign affairs 
committee his ideas on a settlement 
it would be counterproductive to perpetuate a special status 
for germany or to prolong any limitations on german sovereignty 
he said 
discriminatory limitations could only sow the seeds for future 
instability for this reason we are opposed to using these 
discussions to put limits on strictly german military 
capabilities 
he added that limits could be discussed at different 
negotiations at the same time as other confidence building 
measures such measures are usually discussed at the conference 
on security and cooperation in europe they include advance notice 
of military maneuvers arrangements for foreign officers to observe 
them and other ways to assure governments that they will not be the 
