a senatepassed bill to restrict logging in 
americas largest national forest will make the united states 
better able to argue for protection of rain forests elsewhere in 
the world a leading sponsor says 
no longer are we going to be embarrassed about what were 
doing in the tongass sen timothy e wirth dcolo said after 
the senate voted 990 wednesday to approve the tongass timber 
reform act 
the bill would ban logging on more than 670000 acres of 
oldgrowth timber in the 17millionacre alaskan forest which 
besides being the largest us forest is the largest remaining rain 
forest in the temperate zone 
the rain forest larger than west virginia shelters bald 
eagles grizzly bears and prime salmonspawning grounds but it 
also sustains a logging industry that provides 3400 jobs and 
sustains 25 percent of the economy in southeastern alaska the 
states two senators argued 
sponsors say the bill was needed because too much timber was 
being cut from the public land and taxpayers were receiving too 
little in fees because of old exclusive contracts favorable to the 
logging industry 
sens frank h murkowski and ted stevens ralaska said they 
supported the senate compromise version over a stricter version 
passed by the house the white house has also endorsed the senate 
bill which must be reconciled with the house version in 
negotiations 
the vote came after senators set aside a disputed amendment that 
would have required the us forest service to trade mining rights 
in the greens creek area of admiralty island in southeastern alaska 
the exchange with the nativealaskan owned sealaska corp would 
have given the government other mining rights and land including 
the last 6000 acres of oldgrowth timber on admiralty island 
under an agreement worked out among senators the secretary of 
agriculture will try to speed up negotiations on a voluntary land 
and miningrights trade also the senate energy and commerce 
committee will hold hearings beginning june 28 to determine if the 
items to be traded are of comparable value 
the senate bill would modify rather than cancel two existing 
timber sale contracts canceling the exclusive contracts with the 
alaska pulp co and louisiana pacificketchikan would require the 
government to pay higher compensation payments to the two 
companies the office of management and budget says 
besides setting aside protected areas and modifying the major 
contracts the senate bill would eliminate a timber harvest quota 
of 45 billion board feet each decade instead the harvest will be 
more actively managed by the forest service 
wirth and others argued that the current contract enabled the 
two companies to cut only the highest grade timber and sell it at 
below market prices 
the bill also prohibits logging in socalled buffer zones along 
spawning streams 
