<TEXT>
when lt kobori of the japanese imperial 
army died in the arms of his pregnant thai wife blase teenagers 
and staid society matrons alike confessed to breaking down in tears 
and millions of other thais were left with images of the 
japanese very different from those they previously held the 
fanatical samuraistyle warriors of world war ii or todays 
aggressive economic leaders 
since january the thai public has become addicted to a 
serialized tv drama called khuu kam or starcrossed 
lovers the series ended last weekend bangkoks notorious 
traffic jams thinned when episodes were broadcast and social 
engagements often were canceled senior government officials have 
reportedly cut meetings short in order not to miss the program 
fans wrote the producers pleading for a change to the tragic 
ending others proposed marriage to the stars 
the series was based on a still enormously popular novel penned 
by vimol siripaiboon in the late 1960s it tells of a japanese 
officer who falls in love with a thai college undergraduate during 
world war ii 
although kobori carries his army sword even into the bedroom he 
is willing to do anything for his love even neglect some of his 
soldierly duties angsumalin the thai woman hides her own strong 
feelings for him out of thai patriotism until the moment kobori 
dies in an allied bombing raid 
thais already have seen the novel adapted twice on the screen 
and twice for television 
the popularity of the latest version has stemmed in large part 
from the appeal of tongchai mcintyre one of thailands top pop 
singers the handsome son of a thai mother and scottish father put 
in a soulful performance 
many thais say the portrayal of the hero is an effective 
antidote to the hardedged image of japanese in thailand japanese 
are resented by many thais for their aggressive business dealings 
and what thais see as an attempt to gain an economic stranglehold 
on the country 
one thai who has criticized aspects of japanese behavior is 
mechai viravaiyda a leading development expert and former actor 
who portrayed kobori in the first adaptation in 1969 
this is very very good public relations for the japanese 
he said but if you look at koboris character this type of 
japanese has yet to be born 
with koboris notions about the heart being more important 
than flag and country he would have been put in jail or at least 
given a lowranking job in a japanese corporation mechai said 
some in the large japanese community here agree that khuu 
kam makes for some of the best public relations for japanese in 
years 
