<TEXT>
the government said today that the 
fundamentalist islamic opposition has won a clear majority of seats 
in algerias municipal and provincial elections 
the fundamentalist victory in the countrys first multiparty 
elections since independence from france in 1962 was the first 
outright election victory for an islamic fundamentalist party in 
any arab country 
in neighboring tunisia and morocco which have refused to 
recognize the fundamentalists as political parties leaders 
expressed fears that the apparent success of extremism in algeria 
would eventually affect all the countries of northern africa 
in france the ruling socialist party called the fundamentalist 
victory cause for deep concern it cited the fact that numerous 
women had their right to vote confiscated by their fathers or 
husbands 
under the islamic family code men can vote on behalf of their 
wives or daughters without their permission 
sheikh abassi madani president of the victorious islamic 
liberation front thanked the algerian people and government 
wednesday for the high level of political maturity that made 
his victory in tuesdays voting possible 
he demanded the dissolution of the national peoples assembly 
to be followed by legislative elections but he stopped short of 
asking for the resignation of president chadli bendjedid 
national elections are now scheduled for february 1992 the 
government had no immediate response to abassi madanis demand 
the ruling national liberation front for 28 years algerias 
only political party had been widely expected to win because of 
its grip on government machinery and the media as well as its 
greater financial resources it holds every seat in parliament 
but the official algerian news agency said today that with a 
third of the official results tabulated including those from most 
of the large cities the 16monthold islamic salvation front had 
won by absolute or relative majorities 
earlier interior minister mohamed salah mohamedi told reporters 
the fundamentalists had won 327 seats of the first 612 races 
tabulated the ruling party was running second with 208 seats 
the french news agency agence francepresse citing sources 
said the fundamentalists captured councils in algerias four 
largest cities algiers oran constantine and annaba and swept 
45 of the 48 provincial councils 
final official results were expected this evening 
abassi madani dismissed as incidental the decision of two of 
algerias major political parties to call for a boycott of the 
elections 
however it was the boycott by former president ahmed ben 
bellas movement for democracy in algeria and berber leader ait 
ahmeds front of socialist forces that made the fundamentalist 
victory possible 
the average total of abstentions was above 45 percent the 
highest in any algerian election since the end of colonial rule in 
the kabylie region which is ait ahmeds homeland average voter 
participation was less than 15 percent 
the parties urged the boycott because they feared the balloting 
was rigged in favor of the ruling party they also objected to the 
short period of time they were given to prepare for the ballot 
the boycott weighed heavily in the islamic fundamentalist 
victory the state news agency said 
officials of all parties complained wednesday of widespread 
irregularities including multiple voting missing ballots and 
interference at polling places by outsiders and election officials 
it was not clear exactly what the impact of the fundamentalist 
victory would be in algeria a country of 24 million 
politically most major decisions are made by the central 
government local councils cannot for example impose islamic law 
on a local basis 
but the victory clearly has emboldened the fundamentalists who 
are now likely to operate as a governmentinwaiting and expect 
their demands will be taken seriously 
socially the victory is likely to make algerians concentrate 
more on the issue of what kind of society they want 
nonfundamentalists are likely to realize they will need to become 
more active and organized if they want stop the fundamentalists 
advance 
abassi madani a 59yearold philosophy professor denied his 
movement wishes to turn the country into a oneparty religious 
state we guarantee the freedom of all who have ideas on 
algerias future he said 
the islamic salvation front seeks to establish the islamic legal 
code the sharia as law the party assigns women to a subservient 
role none of the fronts 12000 candidates for office in tuesdays 
voting were women 
for months fundamentalist supporters have been accused of 
harassing single women and disrupting nightclubs in algiers 
the party boasts 650000 members many are drawn from the ranks 
of unemployed youth who are attracted by the partys fiery mix of 
islam and politics 
the national liberation front was the sole political party until 
constitutional changes in february 1989 opened the way to competing 
parties 
the party was forced to end its monopoly on power after soldiers 
killed scores of people in october 1988 riots sparked by 
deteriorating economic conditions 
