<TEXT>
the coast guard has tentatively approved 
the experimental use of oileating bacteria on the spill from the 
supertanker mega borg 
state officials had suggested the approach and discussed it 
wednesday with the environmental protection agency coast guard and 
other agencies 
its worth a try anything we can do to clean up the spill 
well try coast guard capt thomas greene said he said 
however he did not consider the technique a major part of the 
cleanup which also involves skimmers booms and chemical 
dispersants 
as the federal onscene coordinator he asked state officials to 
submit a plan today on how they will conduct the test without 
interfering with the salvage efforts in the gulf of mexico 
the process called bioremediation uses naturally occurring 
bacteria to reduce oil to an emulsion of fatty acids this emulsion 
sinks and is consumed by marine life 
bioremediation has been used for years to clean up hazardous 
waste sites treat sewage and wastewater extract oil from tight 
geologic formations and clean some rocks on shore after the exxon 
valdez accident in alaska last year said texas land commissioner 
garry mauro 
but this will be the first time bioremediation has been used in 
the water to clean up an oil spill he said 
now we have the chance to put to real use innovation and new 
technology that can provide all of us with a means to avoid the 
potential environmental devastation of an oil spill mauro said 
greene said the coast guard would provide a boat to scientists 
to apply the sandlike bacteria to the oil slick 
bj buck wynne iii chairman of the texas water commission 
said he expected to mix the bacteria in 100gallon tanks of salt 
water and shoot it through hoses from a coast guard cutter 
wynne and mauro suggested using 100 pounds of the bacteria a day 
for three to four days on freshly spilled oil near the vessel the 
test will cost the state about 50000 mauro said 
</TEXT>
