<TEXT>
hanover a west german industrial city seeking a 
higher international profile was chosen by a onevote margin today 
to be host of expo 2000 an ecologically oriented turnofthe 
century worlds fair 
hanover was selected by the parisbased international bureau of 
expositions in a 2120 vote over toronto canada the only other 
candidate after the italian government decided to drop a campaign 
on behalf of venice 
hanover a northern city of 500000 known for an annual trade 
fair was considered a strong contender because many of the 
exposition bureaus member countries have close economic ties to 
west germany 
the bureaus 43 members who vote by secret ballot include 25 
from europe 11 from the western hemisphere four from africa two 
from asia and one from australia it was not known which two 
members did not vote today 
toronto had argued that it was north americas turn since the 
next two fairs are in europe seville spain in 1992 and 
viennabudapest in 1995 
the bureau formed in 1928 seeks to ensure that contending 
cities have an appropriate site adequate transit government 
backing and enough hotel rooms the winning country then draws up 
final plans and finds sponsors financial and public support 
hanover was the first west german city to contend for the right 
to host an officially sanctioned universal exposition the 
largest type of event overseen by the bureau 
the city has proposed a theme of man nature technology for 
the fair the event is tentatively scheduled to run from june 1 to 
oct 31 providing an estimated 70000 new jobs in the region and 
costing roughly 1 billion 
in the past some cities have backed out as moscow did in the 
1960s clearing the way for canada to play host to its first fair 
in montreal 
late last year canadian prime minister brian mulroney wrote to 
the exposition bureau extolling toronto as a vibrant symbol of 
excellence tolerance humanity and pluralism 
at that time venice was also in the running but the italian 
government withdrew the candidacy earlier this week 
venetians as well as the italian government were divided as to 
whether the expositions estimated 60000 daily visitors would help 
revive the canal city or create unmanageable environmental problems 
</TEXT>
