a political party made up of former 
communists won the opening round of voting for bulgarias first 
freely elected parliament in more than five decades according to 
final results released today 
the governing socialist party formerly known as the communist 
party won the most seats in the 400seat parliament defeating the 
main opposition alliance in direct balloting for candidates and in 
voting for parties 
the socialists won 172 of the 319 seats decided in last 
weekends first round voting final results showed 
under bulgarias complex electoral law half the seats are 
distributed according to the percentage of votes each party 
receives the other half go to individual candidates elected by 
direct ballot 
the results mean the socialist party only needs to win 29 of 81 
candidate races that will be decided in sundays runoff to capture 
an absolute majority in the unicameral grand national assembly or 
parliament 
bulgaria was the only country in the disintegrating soviet bloc 
where the communists who changed their partys name in april 
remained the strongest political force 
the socialist party gained 47 percent of the proportionally 
distributed votes for 97 of the 200 seats contested among the 
parties zhivko stalev head of the central electoral commission 
told reporters the main opposition union of democratic forces was 
a distant second with 36 percent or 75 seats 
finishing third was the mainstream agrarian party with 8 percent 
and thus 16 seats and fourth was the mostly ethnicturkish 
movement for rights and freedoms with 6 percent and 12 seats he 
said 
despite recurrent charges of alleged manipulation and other 
irregularities union of democratic forces leaders accepted the 
returns in principle 
when the socialist victory was first signaled by projections 
earlier this week anticommunist and union of democratic forces 
protesters blocked traffic in sofia claiming the election was 
rigged 
however a majority of western observers said monday that the 
balloting process was essentially fair although some of them 
pinpointed individual cases of infringement of the rules 
