<TEXT>
the muchtouted benefits of lowering cholesterol 
may be especially effective for people who already have heart 
disease according to a study published today 
the findings based on a 10year research project confirm the 
widely held belief that people with low levels of cholesterol in 
their blood are far less likely to die of heart disease than those 
with high cholesterol 
but the study in the new england journal of medicine also shows 
that high cholesterol is especially dangerous when heart arteries 
are already partially clogged with cholesterol buildups 
the study was not intended to see what happens when people 
change their cholesterol levels 
the researchers wrote however that it suggests that the 
potential impact of changes in lipid cholesterol levels on the 
risk of death from cardiovascular disease may be considerably 
greater for men with preexisting cardiovascular disease than for 
healthy men 
the analysis based on the lipid research clinics prevalence 
study was conducted by dr juha pekkanen and others from the 
university of north carolina 
in the study desirable cholesterol levels were under 200 while 
high levels were over 240 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

