<TEXT>
the bush administration announced today it 
will not impose economic sanctions on india for trade barriers the 
united states deems offensive 
us trade representative carla hills termed indias barriers to 
investment by americans and other foreigners and its exclusion of 
us insurance companies as an unreasonable burden on us commerce 
but she said that retaliation was inappropriate at this time 
given ongoing global free trade talks she said the administration 
would try to resolve its dispute with india as part of those 
discussions 
those discussions being held under the auspices of the 
96nation general agreement on tariffs and trade are due to wrap 
up at the end of this year india is considered a key participant 
in these talks known as the uruguay round because of its 
influence over other developing countries 
hills said indias announcement on may 31 that it would remove 
some of its barriers to foreign investment was a hopeful sign 
our message that foreign investment brings jobs technology 
and prosperity may be getting through hills said i hope this 
attitude will be reflected in indias approach to these issues in 
the uruguay round 
the administrations decision was relayed on wednesday to abid 
hussain indias new ambassador to washington 
the administration faced a june 16 deadline to decide whether to 
boost tariffs on indian imports or impose other retaliatory trade 
sanctions because of indias refusal to negotiate the dispute 
the case against india involves that nations barriers to 
foreign investment and its refusal to allow american insurance 
companies to do business in the country 
india was one of three countries placed on a trade hit list 
last year by the administration for erecting the most offensive 
trade barriers against american products 
the other two countries japan and brazil both successfully 
reached agreements with the united states to remove the offending 
barriers however india has refused to negotiate under threat of 
us sanctions which are provided by a section of the 1988 trade 
law known as super 301 
while the decision removes the possibility of economic 
retaliation immediately the administration in april renamed india 
to a hit list for the current year citing the same trade 
barriers the deadline for reaching a conclusion on that action 
will not come until june 1991 
the decision to cite only india in the second round of 
negotiations and to leave japan off the list triggered heavy 
protests in congress where japans huge 49 billion trade surplus 
with the united states has attracted attention 
the administration contended that japan had negotiated in good 
faith to remove barriers to sales of american satellites 
supercomputers and wood products in japan and therefore should not 
be targeted again 
the administration also pledged to press forward with separate 
discussions on broadranging structural trade barriers with japan 
those discussions are focusing on such issues as increasing 
penalties for antimonopolistic practices streamlining the 
countrys retail distribution procedures and making other changes 
to expand opportunities for foreign businesses 
there have been complaints in recent days that the talks with 
japan on structural impediments to trade had bogged down a final 
report on these talks is scheduled to be issued in july 
