<DOCNO> AP900614-0080 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today barred manufacturers 
from giving discounts to wholesalers and not to retailers when the 
discounts are unrelated to any savings for the supplier or to the 
wholesalers costs 
the court unanimously upheld a 135 million antitrust award 
texaco inc was ordered to pay to 12 service stations in the 
spokane wash area 
justice john paul stevens writing for the court said there was 
no evidence that texacos discounts constituted a reasonable 
reimbursement for the value to texaco of the wholesalers 
marketing functions 
texacos appeal had been supported by leading business groups 
including the national association of manufacturers and the 
american petroleum institute 
they had said a defeat for texaco could undermine the most 
common distributional arrangement in american business the dual 
channel system in which a manufacturer or supplier sells to 
wholesalers at discounted prices lower than those it charges direct 
purchasing retailers 
but the court today said texacos discounts amounted to illegal 
price discrimination barred by a federal antitrust law the 
robinsonpatman act 
a federal jury ordered texaco to pay 449900 a sum that was 
tripled by the judge to 135 million in accord with the act 
the 12 service station dealers that sued said from 1972 to 1981 
they were placed at an unfair competitive disadvantage because 
texaco supplied gasoline to two spokanearea wholesalers john 
dompier oil co and gull oil co at discounts ranging from 25 
cents to 575 cents per gallon less than texaco charged the 
retailers 
dompier sold the gasoline to other retailers under the texaco 
trademark gull marketed it under private brand names 
the 12 service stations said they suffered because at least part 
of the discounts were passed on to consumers by competing retailers 
who bought from dompier and gull 
texaco argued that the discounts were legitimate since they were 
available to all wholesalers who purchased from the oil comany 
giant 
stevens today noted there was evidence the services offered by 
gull and dompier were insubstantial and did not justify the 
discount 
for example there was evidence that gulls role as a middleman 
amounted only to engaging in paper transactions and in fact 
texaco delivered gasoline directly to some of dompiers customers 
the case is texaco vs hasbrouck 872048 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

