the new york stock exchange will begin trading 
stocks outside its normal hours and off its trading floor later 
this year a first in its nearly 200year history sources 
confirmed today 
the plans are an attempt to recapture trading volume in big 
board stocks from foreign markets especially london and tokyo as 
the world moves toward aroundtheclock trading 
the new trading will be conducted electronically and may bypass 
the specialists the floor traders through whom stock transactions 
are routed currently said officials familiar with the plan who 
asked not to be named 
the plan first was reported in the new york times 
nyse spokesman richard torrenzano declined to confirm the 
report however he said the exchange has been studying the 
possibility of offhours trading for two years 
if we see a need by our customers to have an offhour trading 
system we will move very innovatively and quickly to meet that 
customer demand he said 
the times said the exchange plans to begin two limited 
afterhours trading sessions sometime this year with different 
rules applying than during daytime trading 
sometime in 1991 the exchange plans to conduct auctions of each 
big board stock at 8 pm midnight and 5 am new york time the 
newspaper said each stock would trade only once at each auction 
with all trades combined at a single agreed price 
the three auction times would coincide with the start of the 
tokyo business day the middle of the tokyo day and the early part 
of the london business day 
it is estimated that 15 million to 20 million shares of nyse 
stocks trade each day outside of exchange hours average volume 
during the exchanges 930 am to 4 pm session has been running 
at about 160 million shares recently 
