<TEXT>
a human rights group urged the hong kong 
authorities thursday to abolish capital punishment before this 
british colony reverts to chinese rule in 1997 
although the law still exists hong kong has not carried out 
capital punishment since 1966 and death sentences are commuted to 
life imprisonment 
the hong kong branch of amnesty international said it was 
apprehensive of the use of the penalty after 1997 because it is 
still widely imposed and carried out in china 
amnesty international opposes the death penalty as a violation 
of the right of life it said in a statement it is also the 
ultimate form of cruel inhumane and degrading punishment 
the call for its abolishment was contained in the human rights 
groups submission on the territorys proposed bill of rights 
which is expected to be enacted into law this year 
the bill was unveiled by the government in march in a move to 
reassure people here that their human rights will be safeguarded 
after the chinese takeover 
china has warned it would repeal the bill if contravenes the 
basic law the constitution for hong kongs post1997 
administration 
the chinese government has pledged to retain hong kongs legal 
and capitalistic systems for 50 years after 1997 
