here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken thursday by the supreme court 
 
sobriety checkpoints 
 
the court ruled that privacy rights of motorists are not 
violated when police try to curb drunken driving by stopping them 
at sobriety checkpoints the supreme court ruled today 
the 63 ruling upheld michigans sobriety checkpoint program 
and by extension similar programs in most states 
the case is state police vs sitz 881897 
 
welfare 
 
the court allowed the bush administration to limit how much 
welfare aid some needy families receive 
by a 54 vote the court said social security benefits paid to 
children must be considered in determining a familys eligibility 
for benefits under the governments aid to families with dependent 
chidren program 
the case is sullivan vs stroop 89535 
 
pollution 
 
the court ruled the government may impose severe fines against 
air polluters even when federal officials are slow to decide on 
proposals for cleaning up the atmosphere 
in the pollution case the justices upheld by a 90 vote the 
environmental protection agencys power to seek fines of up to 
25000 a day against a general motors plant in massachusetts 
however the impact of the ruling for future cases may be 
limited the house and senate have passed separate bills revising 
the federal clean air act that establish new timetables to address 
the kind of problem at issue in the general motors case 
the case is general motors vs us 89369 
 
medicaid 
 
the court ruled that hospitals and nursing homes may sue in 
federal court to challenge how a staterun medicaid program 
reimburses their costs 
the justices by a 54 vote let a virginia hospital association 
invoke a federal civil rights law in suing the state over 
virginias medicaid reimbursement rates 
officials from most of the 50 states had urged the court to rule 
against the association they said allowing such lawsuits could 
affect hundreds of millions of dollars in federal and state 
funding and lead to a litigation explosion 
the case is wilder vs virginia hospital association 882043 
 
discounts 
 
the court barred manufacturers from giving discounts to 
wholesalers and not to retailers when the discounts are unrelated 
to any savings for the supplier or to the wholesalers costs 
the court unanimously upheld a 135 million antitrust award 
texaco inc was ordered to pay to 12 service stations in the 
spokane wash area 
the case is texaco vs hasbrouck 872048 
