<TEXT>
this city of monuments statues and memorials 
has a new attraction to stir the emotions and evoke the glories of 
the past 
this newest of washingtons monuments 22 of the original 24 
columns from the us capitol literally had to be pulled from the 
mud of the anacostia river and painstakingly stripped of 35 coats 
of white paint 
now after a mighty effort by a few people the columns stand on 
the highest point of a great meadow at the national arboretum 
cleaned up repaired and splendid again holding up nothing but sky 
and glory set between the columns are 500 marble slabs once used 
as steps on the senate wing of the capitol 
in the middle of all this is a small fountain from which water 
flows into a reflecting pool designed so that the full image of the 
columns is mirrored in the water 
the national capitol columns as they are called were dedicated 
wednesday with all the pomp due a newborn shrine the air force 
band played an allservice color guard presented the flag the 
president sent a message and heat put the audience into a patriotic 
sweat 
it is most fitting that the columns will have a permanent new 
home said clayton yeutter the secretary of agriculture they 
are a spectacular addition to the scenery of our great city 
bill allen architectural historian of the capitol was on hand 
to supply the history of the 10ton sandstone columns and a long 
one they have had twentyseven presidents from martin van buren 
to dwight d eisenhower took the oath of office in their shadow 
when they were first installed on the east front of the capitol 
in 1826 congressmen left their benches to help pull the strong 
carriage on which the columns had been placed up capitol hill 
the columns were the finishing touch to the rebuilding of the 
capitol after the british burned the house and senate wings in 
1814 the columns were put between the two wings in the rotunda 
which was completed in 1824 
sam rayburn the longtime speaker of the house went out of the 
capitol every evening to look at and be inspired by the columns 
which are unadorned except for acanthus leaves carved into the caps 
the columns were the principal feature of the capitol until a 
new front was put on in 1958 and completed just in time for john f 
kennedys inauguration in 1961 
the columns replaced by bigger ones made of marble were 
unceremoniously taken to the capitol power plant and lay there for 
15 years in 1973 they were trucked to the banks of the anacostia 
river and left to sink in the mud 
a determined woman ethel garrett campaigned for more than 20 
years to have the columns put on public display at the arboretum 
she died without seeing her plan come to fruition 
betty rae chairman of the project said all of the nearly 2 
million spent on the project was raised from private donors many 
of whom were at the ceremony wednesday 
the columns will draw people to the arboretum who never would 
have come to the arboretum she said the national arboretum 300 
acres of great trees and shrubs is one of washingtons bestkept 
secrets located miles away from the citys more famous attractions 
</TEXT>
