<TEXT>
negotiators at eastwest talks on 
reducing europes conventional forces are close to agreement on 
overall limits for the number of tanks and armored combat vehicles 
diplomats said thursday 
they said they expected imminent formal agreement on ceilings in 
the two weapons categories and said this would speed negotiations 
for an initial agreement at the talks by the end of the year 
the negotiations on conventional forces in europe are designed 
to reduce troops and nonnuclear weapons of the two military 
alliances from the atlantic ocean to the ural mountains 
the 16 member nations of the north atlantic treaty organization 
and seven warsaw pact countries are taking part 
the breakthrough came from the french and the poles 
their proposal suggests an overall ceiling for armored combat 
vehicles of 30000 for each side and a ceiling of 20000 tanks for 
each side 
it sets minimum weight parameters of 165 tons for tanks 
regardless of whether they have tracks or wheels 
french chief delegate francois plaisant said at a joint news 
conference with polands wlodzimierz konarski there was informal 
but overall consensus on the proposal 
a press statement by soviet delegation leader oleg a grinevski 
said an important step has doubtlessly been made this 
solution means substantial progress at the vienna negotiations 
a minor setback occurred however at a closeddoor meeting of 
delegates from all 23 countries at which the proposal had been 
expected to be made final said a western diplomat speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
the soviet side said it first wanted to see an equipment list 
that is to accompany the agreement the diplomat said no one at 
the soviet delegation could be reached for comment 
the western diplomat called the development a negative step 
but expressed hope it could be worked out quickly at current 
informal meetings 
the breakthrough came after weeks when negotiators from both 
sides complained petty bargaining was slowing the talks western 
diplomats said the soviets appeared to be dragging their feet until 
the future security allegiance of a united germany is decided 
but the diplomats said they had detected a willingness to move 
forward in recent weeks 
both sides hope to have an agreement ready for signing by 
december when leaders from 35 nations including the 23 involved 
in the vienna talks are scheduled to meet in paris 
the other 12 participants are neutral and nonaligned countries 
in europe that also would be affected by reducing tensions on the 
continent 
finding common definitions for tanks and other armaments has 
been a contentious issue at the vienna talks 
thursdays proposal no longer makes a distinction between 
armored troop carriers and other armored vehicles removing a 
further obstacle 
konarski said the text in a future treaty will include a list of 
the arms they would carry classifying all the weapons the two 
sides now have 
he said this would be unprecedented in eastwest relations he 
said these lists would then become the basis for the reductions 
according to us estimates the west now has 23600 tanks and 
the warsaw pact 52500 and 34025 armored combat vehicles to the 
warsaw pacts 59400 
konarski said the use of broader categories of definitions was 
the only way to conclude a deal under the circumstances but he and 
plaisant said many issues remain to be resolved before a final 
agreement can be signed 
