<TEXT>
hospitals and nursing homes may challenge a 
states medicaid reimbursement system the supreme court ruled 
thursday in a decision that could have a major financial impact 
the justices in a 54 vote said the virginia hospital 
association may use a federal civil rights law to sue virginia over 
the states medicaid payment rates 
at a time of soaring medical costs and an increasing demand for 
medicaid services the decision could force the federal and state 
governments to cough up more money for the program that provides 
medical care for the poor 
this should increase the amount of reimbursement that 
hospitals will get for providing medicaid patients with care 
said fredric j entin general counsel for the american hospital 
association 
he said he could not estimate how much reimbursements might rise 
if hospitals are successful with their lawsuits 
if the hospital association wins its case in federal court the 
states hospitals would get 25 million to 27 million more per 
year in medicaid reimbursements said laurens sartoris association 
president about half would come from the federal government and 
half from state coffers virginia hospitals now get about 230 
million from medicaid he said 
in this fiscal year total medicaid expenses for the nation are 
expected to approach 71 billion about 56 percent borne by the 
federal government and the rest by the states 
hospitals in colorado pennsylvania and michigan have won 
lawsuits similar to the virginia hospital associations though 
some of the decisions are on appeal cases also are pending in 
wisconsin oregon and ohio said mary babich a spokeswoman for the 
american hospital association 
officials from most states had urged the supreme court to rule 
against the virginia association they said allowing such lawsuits 
could affect hundreds of millions of dollars in federal and state 
funding and lead to a litigation explosion 
the medicaid program in almost every state is having financial 
difficulties said jeff harris a researcher for the medicaid 
management institute which is part of the american public welfare 
association 
this opens the door to tremendous increases in costs he 
said adding that it also ties the hands of state legislatures by 
allowing judicial rate setting for hospitals nursing homes and 
doctors 
sartoris disagreed saying i dont think the floodgates are 
going to open 
he added that it wouldnt surprise me that some states 
would file suit but he said providers have a tremendous burden 
to prove that the states program doesnt meet the federal standard 
whether the supreme court decision would help physicians who 
might challenge medicaid reimbursements was unclear harris said it 
would but martin a donlan an attorney for the virginia 
association was doubtful 
the court led by justice william j brennan said congress 
never intended to bar medicaid care providers from suing in federal 
court when reimbursement disputes arise 
the court said congress gave health care providers the right to 
sue in federal court when it amended the medicaid act in 1980 
that amendment introduced by sen david boren dokla 
requires states to reimburse health care providers according to 
rates the state finds and makes assurances satisfactory to the 
secretary of health and human services are reasonable and 
adequate 
writing for the majority brennan said the amendment creates a 
right enforceable in a private cause of action to have the 
state adopt rates that it finds are reasonable and adequate rates 
to meet the costs of an efficient and economical health care 
provider 
brennan was joined by justices byron r white thurgood 
marshall harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices sandra day 
oconnor antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy dissented 
in its 1986 lawsuit the virginia hospital association sued the 
state alleging that the toolow rates violate the federal medicaid 
act and the rights of participating hospitals to due process 
virginia officials sought to have the suit dismissed contending 
that only health care recipients not individual or associated 
health care providers have the right to sue under the medicaid 
act 
