<DOCNO> AP900614-0183 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the senate judiciary committee on thursday 
endorsed a constitutional amendment to require a balanced federal 
budget 
the amendment was sent to the full senate by a vote of 113 
if approved by twothirds of the senate and the house and then 
by 38 states the amendment would prohibit federal spending from 
exceeding revenues except in time of war or if both chambers waive 
the requirement by a 60 percent vote 
it would also require that a majority of each chamber of 
congress instead of just a majority of those present and voting 
approve any tax increase 
the amendment would take effect in the second fiscal year after 
ratification 
balancedbudget amendments have been approved before by the 
committee the provision most recently was subjected to a full 
senate vote in 1986 and failed by one vote it passed the senate in 
1982 but died in the house 
thursdays action came as house senate and white house 
negotiators continued their budget summit in the capitol aimed 
at reducing the federal deficit democrats and republicans have 
been unable to agree on how to bring the fiscal gap below 100 
billion never mind zero 
they met for less than two hours and participants said they 
discussed a variety of budget process reforms without reaching any 
agreements the talks are scheduled to resume next tuesday 
because congress normal budget process has been sidetracked 
during the lengthy negotiations the senate approved a resolution 
thursday night to keep a legislative backlog from building 
by voice vote the senate approved the technical equivalent of a 
budget for the fiscal year beginning oct 1 but the document was 
devoid of the policies and fiscal decisions a budget normally 
embodies those details to be filled in later if the summit 
succeeds 
the purpose of the vote supported by the white house was to 
let the congress begin work on its annual spending bills for 
federal agencies 
the house on may 1 approved a 12 trillion budget spelling out 
federal spending priorities including a shift from military 
spending to domestic programs the senate then stopped short 
because of the bipartisan budget talks 
the senate resolution approved thursday night simply sets a 503 
billion total target same as the current year for domestic and 
defense programs outside of entitlement programs like social 
security and other spending not set annually 
both must agree on a single resolution for it to become binding 
on the two chambers it doesnt require the presidents signature 
house speaker thomas s foley dwash said thursday that the 
house did not intend to abandon its plan housesenate talks are 
expected to begin next week even as the budget summit continues 
