<TEXT>
a political movement associated with the 
churchgoing conservative middle class is trying to fill the vacuum 
left by the collapse of communist parties in eastern europe 
leaders of the movement say centerright christian democratic 
parties like those in western europe and scandinavia could become 
the dominant political force in the former soviet bloc 
wladyslaw silanowicki chairman of polands christian 
democratic party of labor said christian democracy should be one 
of the basic centers of building pluralism and normality in 
political life after decades of oneparty communist party rule 
christian democratic parties were born after world war i 
particularly among roman catholics in western europe they urged 
christians to participate in politics based on social teachings of 
the religion 
the doctrine advocates cooperation between employers and 
employees rejecting both marxism and unfettered capitalism 
it differs with the social democratic tradition which dates 
from the 1870s and is closely tied to trade union movements mainly 
in its attitude toward state intervention in the economy social 
democrats are more inclined to advocate state ownership of major 
industries 
east germanys christian democrats were the big winners in 
parliamentary elections in march 
democratic forum the winner in hungary that same month is more 
of a mix but emphasized christian values in its campaign it 
formed a governing coalition with two sympathetic parties one 
called the christian democrats 
in czechoslovakia christian democrats did not achieve their 
goal of finishing second to civic forum in this months election 
but did place third after the communists 
in polish politics solidarity towers above all groups its 
support ranges from morally conservative marketoriented catholics 
to liberal intellectuals and populistminded workers whose ideal is 
something on the lines of socialist sweden 
political aides of solidarity leader lech walesa have tried 
recently to draw centerright elements together in a political 
union called the center alliance with strong christian democratic 
overtones 
silanowickis party formed before world war ii has received 
quiet encouragement from the catholic church 
romania and bulgaria have budding christian democratic parties 
and one has been formed in moscow 
antongiulio de robertis an official of the christian democrat 
international in rome said it had established links with christian 
democrats throughout eastern europe 
prior to last year we had ties with skeleton committees of 
precommunist political groupings that had been kept alive by 
emigre communities he said with the liberation of eastern 
europe these parties returned to their respective countries and 
continued to work 
a reaction to communism accounts for part of the support said 
carl ordnung a christian democratic activist working for lothar de 
maiziere the new prime minister of east germany 
its because these parties are christian parties he said 
christianity to a certain extent is quite the opposite of marxism 
and communism after this whole progressive attitude of communists 
people say now let us stick to a more conservative program 
in east germany the christian democrats confounded pollsters by 
overtaking the social democrats in the last days of the campaign 
they benefited from ties to the christian democratic union of west 
germany and its leader chancellor helmut kohl who advocated 
speedy german reunification 
bruno orsini head of the international department of the 
christian democrat international in rome sees a parallel between 
eastern europe now and western europe in the late 1940s 
in the period immediately after world war ii the two 
countries which had been ruled by dictatorships chose the christian 
democratic path to achieve their reconstruction he said 
both germans and italians overcame the bitterness of the nazi 
period through their adoption of what was a christian democratic 
value the belief in unity 
now it is the same for eastern europe the hopes of east 
europeans who have escaped oppression after years of authoritarian 
rule and underdevelopment are based on liberty and solidarity 
both these values are central to christian democracy orsini 
said 
advocates say it appeals to people who suffered under extremist 
regimes 
we are a centrist party silanowicki said we are 
decidedly opponents of monoparties regardless of whether they are 
leftist like the communist party or rightist like the totalitarian 
parties of fascist italy and nazi germany 
sandor keresztes chairman of the hungarian christian democrats 
sees the movement as a counter to divisive nationalism in eastern 
europe 
with so many ethnic hungarians in neighboring countries this 
is especially vital to his party keresztes said 
christian democratic parties deny they are controlled by any 
church but tend to be linked to roman catholicism and follow 
vatican teachings on such issues as abortion and pornography 
pope john paul ii a native of poland went to czechoslovakia in 
april and plans to visit hungary and poland next year he has 
expressed hope that new public policies in eastern europe will 
reject both communism and excessive western consumerism 
</TEXT>
