<TEXT>
a threatened scientific boycott over us 
travel restrictions on foreigners infected with the aids virus has 
failed but the policy will remain a major issue at this weeks 
international aids meeting 
the french and swiss governments the european parliament and 
other groups had urged scientists to boycott because of us 
immigration policy 
but officials say registration for the sixth international 
conference on aids which opens wednesday will come close to the 
original estimate of 12000 
among those registered are luc montagnier and other members of 
frances pasteur institute one of the worlds leading aids 
research centers 
only 50 research papers were withdrawn from the 2500 studies 
originally submitted conference spokesman dana van gorder said 
no one wants to see the law interfere with the work of this 
conference van gorder said people are coming here to improve 
the work they are doing in response to aids they felt this is the 
highest responsibility 
so do some two dozen aids activist groups which announced plans 
to attend the fiveday meeting to protest the immigration policy 
and publicize their claims of government inaction and drug company 
profits on aids medications 
not joining the boycott was a painful decision for us said 
tom cunningham a member of the new york chapter of the aids 
coalition to unleash power better known as act up but we do 
need the opportunity to challenge aids researchers and the 
pharmaceutical companies 
the controversy is over a 1987 senate amendment ordering the 
public health service to place infection by hiv the virus that 
causes aids on the list of contagious diseases that may bar 
foreigners from entering the united states 
the list also includes leprosy tuberculosis and five sexually 
transmitted diseases 
the restriction has been condemned by scores of aids groups 
including the national commission on aids as an infringement on 
human rights the commissions chairman dr june osborn said the 
policy fosters the impression that aids and hiv infection can be 
easily transmitted 
a number of groups involved in aids education programs and care 
of aids patients are boycotting the conference 
the list includes almost 100 nongovernmental organizations 
including the international planned parenthood foundation and the 
league of red cross and red crescent societies a genevabased 
federation of red cross organizations from 149 countries 
the world health organization also criticized the immigration 
policy and for a time contemplated backing out as cosponsor of 
the conference 
dr bruce dick health department director at the league of red 
cross and red crescent said many of the boycotting groups could 
lend valuable groundlevel experience to scientists at the 
conference 
the most negative thing about us not participating is the 
missed opportunity to use a big conference like this to form 
partnerships he said 
dick said the society had 40 people from 30 countries at last 
years conference in montreal and originally had planned to send 
more representatives to san francisco 
the bush administration twice has tried to blunt the outcry 
last year the immigration and naturalization service adopted a 
waiver policy that would allow those infected with hiv to stay in 
the united states up to 30 days for business purposes conferences 
medical treatment and family visits 
the waiver also offered foreign visitors greater 
confidentiality eliminating permanent identifying marks on their 
passports 
in april the ins said it would issue new 10day visas for those 
coming to this country for professional or scientific conferences 
those applying for the visas are not required to state if they are 
infected with hiv 
the new visa plan cooled some of the protest but many remain 
opposed to any singling out of aids or hivinfected people 
the administration has made some efforts but we still find 
the policy objectionable said sue lucas coordinator of the 
united kingdom aids consortium for the third world a group of 40 
british organizations with aids programs in developing countries 
we are particularly concerned that this type of discrimination 
in the united states would have an impact on discrimination in 
other countries she said 
the controversy has brought calls for the administration to 
remove aids and hiv infection from the list 
legislative leaders point to a government accounting office 
opinion that the secretary of health and human services can remove 
the restriction but administration officials maintain a directive 
from congress cannot be eliminated that way 
rep j roy rowland dga introduced legislation in april that 
would give the department of health and human services authority 
over deciding which diseases are on the list 
it is my opinion the administration would like a way out of 
this said rowland the present rule reflects adversely on the 
united states which has been a leader in scientific and medical 
research for many years 
the united states always has placed health and social limits on 
those entering the country in the late 18th century a prohibition 
existed on prostitutes and beggars 
today 33 separate categories limit travel to this country such 
as medical conditions mental disease political ideology bigamy 
and homosexuality 
during the wave of immigration through new yorks ellis island 
people were forced to run up and down stairs to see if they winded 
easily a sign of tuberculosis ins spokesman duke austin said 
the present law which dates back to 1952 first barred those 
with tuberculosis and leprosy by 1987 the list included five 
sexually transmitted diseases gonorrhea infectious syphilis 
chancroid granuloma inguinale and lymphogranuloma venereum 
aids was added to the list by the public health service in june 
of that year hiv infection was placed on the list by congressional 
mandate in august 
thirtythree other countries place entrance restrictions on 
foreigners with aids or hiv infection usually on those seeking 
extended stays iraq demands aids tests for anyone staying more 
than five days those seeking permanent residence or a stay longer 
than 12 months in australia also must be tested bahrain tests 
certain foreign workers such as hotel staff and hairdressers 
those seeking permanent entry to the united states must have a 
full physical examination but visitors are not tested for disease 
basically it is an honor system said austin there is no 
way to tell unless an inspector ascertains through the discovery of 
drugs or certain physical characteristics that the inspection 
should be pressed further 
opponents of us policy say the issue is one of setting a 
standard for the rest of the world they hope a final resolution 
can be reached before 1992 when another international aids 
conference is scheduled for boston 
to many countries the united states is a leader in terms of 
its policies said dick of the league of red cross and red 
crescent it is essential that we have nondiscriminatory 
policies because it is through nondiscrimination that we are going 
to control this disease 
</TEXT>
