<TEXT>
norma chavarria a former teacher has 
opened a makeshift store to keep going until president violeta 
barrios de chamorro makes the stalled economy run and times get 
better 
we have to give violeta time she said how can a 
president do in 40 days what the sandinistas couldnt do in 10 
years my husband and i are confident things will get better in 
about six months 
mrs chavarria 24 leaned on the counter in the dirtfloored 
wooden shack where she sells single cakes of laundry soap soft 
drinks envelopes of soup mix and other inexpensive items 
a neighbor who had just come in said thats right those 
sandinistas didnt do anything except make us go to meetings a 
meeting for this a meeting for that we have to give a little time 
to poor dona violeta 
mrs chavarrias husband jose is a bricklayer who brings home 
20 a month slightly more than she earned as a grade school 
teacher her teaching papers were lost they moved here recently 
from esteli so they decided she should open the store 
many people seem to share the guarded optimism of mrs chavarria 
and the neighbor but there also is a show me attitude that 
good times are not just around the corner 
nicaraguans voted the sandinistas out feb 25 and inflation 
still is high nearly two months after mrs chamorros proamerican 
government was inaugurated 
inflation reached 36000 percent in 1988 then declined to 1800 
percent in 1989 
francisco mayorga president of the central bank now gauges it 
weekly his figures were 47 percent for the first week of may then 
17 percent 12 and 11 for the next three 
mayorga who was educated at yale and devised mrs chamorros 
economic recovery plan accused the sandinistas of using the 
twomonth transition period to undermine the new government 
he said they spent money wildly and printed more to cover the 
deficit 
president bush signed a 300 million aid package may 26 the 
first 60 million arrived quickly and between may 25 and may 31 
the black market price of a dollar declined from 310000 cordobas 
to 290000 
the exchange houses are supplying dollars again thats why it 
went down said jose gutierrez one of two dozen currency dealers 
on a street near the mexican embassy 
gutierrez and his colleagues wave wads of cordobas at passing 
motorists and police look the other way 
another sign of improvement is a 20 percent increase in planted 
farm acreage over last year mayorga said food production fell 
steadily under the sandinistas 
on the negative side nicaraguas currency has been devalued 
frequently since mrs chamorro took office the parallel exchange 
rate which governs most dollar transactions had gone from 70800 
cordobas to 226600 by may 31 
some chamorro supporters are beginning to grumble 
