<TEXT>
a new york stock exchange report that found 
little fault with program trading and recommended the securities 
and exchange commission rule over stockindex futures did little to 
advance the political debate over the two issues 
supporters of the embattled commodity futures trading commission 
engaged in a jurisdictional battle with the sec over 
stockrelated futures said wedensday the report backed their 
arguments while some sec partisans said it doesnt go far enough to 
support theirs 
but politicians and others who have been dealing with proposals 
for broad market reforms since after the 1987 crash indicated the 
new study would have little or no effect on positions already taken 
among the recommendations of the stock exchanges 18member 
panel was the establishment of a single regulator for stocks and 
stockrelated futures legislation for such a change is being 
considered by congress 
publicly senate and house members were restrained in their 
comments about the report by the panel which was ordered to 
investigate market volatility following the stock market plunge 
last oct 13 
sen donald w riegle dmich chairman of the banking housing 
and urban affairs committee said the senate panel would review 
these recommendations carefully 
rep edward j markey dmass chairman of the house 
subcommittee that oversees the sec called for passage of pending 
market reform legislation to bolster the secs enforcement powers 
congressional aides who spoke only on the condition of 
anonymity said the report would be interpreted differently by 
supporters of the sec or cftc to bolster their respective causes 
itll be used on both sides of the argument said one senate 
aide familiar with the issues i dont think its going to have 
any effect on the pending legislation 
recommendations by the panel headed by general motors corp 
chairman roger b smith included consolidating regulation of 
stocks and stockrelated futures under one federal agency to 
improve investor confidence 
program trading strategies involving simultaneous trading of 
huge amounts of stock and stockindex futures have been blamed for 
causing or worsening big price swings in the stock market 
such trading was criticized after the oct 13 1989 market drop 
when the dow jones industrial average fell 190 points and blamed 
for worsening the oct 19 1987 crash in which the dow fell 508 
points 
legislation to put stocks and index futures under one regulator 
is bitterly opposed by the cftc the chicago futures exchanges and 
members of house and senate agriculture committees that oversee the 
cftc 
i think this bill builds our case against switching 
jurisdiction said a senate agriculture committee aide the 
panel found no evidence that a single regulator would affect 
volatility 
however the aide noted there was no evidence that 
consolidating regulatory authority would prevent a future stock 
market crash 
that contradicts the belief that congress needs to act on 
switching authority to prevent one said the aide 
that point was echoed by a spokesman for the commodity futures 
trading commission 
a couple of the recommendations were not supported by the 
analysis said cftc spokesman david gary he said the report 
found no evidence that shifting regulatory authority for stock 
index futures from the cftc to the sec affects market volatility 
but recommended doing so to improve investor confidence whats 
the basis 
on the issue of program trading said gary i think we will be 
in the same corner as the panel 
the nyse panel found nothing inherently wrong with program 
trading indicating it was more of a public relations problem than 
a threat to market stability 
a market reform bill passed by the house contains a provision 
for curbing program trading during periods of extreme market 
volatility the senate version of the bill which has stalled in 
committee contains no program trading provision 
markey a strong opponent of program trading didnt address the 
program trading aspect of the report but he said the panels 
report makes a compelling case for cracking down on intermarket 
trading abuses like front running 
front running is the trading practice of taking advantage of 
advance knowledge of a large and potentially marketmoving customer 
order in one market by taking an offsetting position in another 
market 
