<TEXT>
americans are worried about paying bills run up 
in the 80s and pessimistic about the 90s according to a poll 
done for financial planners 
the findings were not unexpected said robert a hewitt 
chairman of the atlantabased international association of 
financial planners the group commissioned the survey by the gallup 
organization 
i think those of us who deal with the public on a daily basis 
weve been pretty much aware of it hewitt said 
the poll being released today found 46 percent of the 
respondents expressed worry about their ability to meet all of 
their financial responsibilities and 52 percent said they were 
concerned about outliving their retirement savings 
baby boomers had more anxiety than most among respondents 
between the ages of 35 and 44 59 percent were worried about their 
ability to meet financial responsibilities and 62 percent were 
concerned about outliving their savings the survey said 
hewitt called that age bracket triple squeeze boomers 
because they are having to deal with the costs of raising children 
and taking care of their aging parents as well as tending to their 
own needs and desires 
all of a sudden they have this discretionary income and 
discover gosh im going to have to pay for college for little 
johnny hewitt said 
college costs have risen beyond the reach of most american 
families and severe inflation is likely to be a problem in this 
decade according to 80 percent of respondents 
as a result 61 percent said they were less inclined to take 
financial risks than during the 1980s the survey said 
conducted in april among 1058 households in a random sample and 
an additional 600 with incomes of at least 50000 the survey had 
a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percent 
along with the concerns about longterm security americans are 
starting to increase their savings rate hewitt said adding that 
he is a staunch advocate of saving more 
im not suggesting spending less im suggesting we go on a 
cash and carry basis a more prudent spending habit he said in 
an interview from new york 
maybe youre going out to eat three times a week hewitt 
said for example maybe you can go out two times a week or three 
times a week at a less expensive place 
were not going to kill the restaurant business by doing 
that 
