<TEXT>
delawares bank commissioner says the state 
will cooperate with a federal agency that has suggested banks be 
prohibited or restricted from underwriting insurance despite a 
delaware law that allows it 
the federal deposit insurance corp has proposed regulations on 
the subject but they have never been implemented state bank 
commissioner keith h ellis said wednesday the writers of the 
delaware law had copies of the fdics proposals when the law was 
written 
ellis reviewed the state law monday with fdic officials 
we discussed the safeguards that were in the delaware 
legislation and the fact that those were put in the legislation 
with the proposed rules of the fdic before us ellis said 
ellis would not discuss the details of the meeting but said all 
parties expressed a spirit of cooperation 
we discussed what was in the bill and the types of things 
well be looking at as the bill begins to take effect ellis 
said adding he does not foresee any changes in the law no more 
meetings are scheduled 
the scope of regulatory authority in the state office and 
that of the fdic is i believe to be sufficient to address any 
concerns that we will discuss he said 
nonetheless fdic chairman william seidman plans to have his 
staff recommend that banks either be prohibited from underwriting 
insurance or the activity be limited to subsidiaries whose sources 
of capital have been separated from the bank spokeswoman caryl a 
austrian said 
the delaware law allows statechartered banks to sell and 
underwrite insurance through a subsidiary department or division 
the law allows any bank to put up to 25 percent of its capital 
into the insurance operation but the assets liabilities and 
records of the insurance subsidiary must be kept separate from the 
bank 
in a statement seidman said he was concerned about extending 
fdic protection to banks with insurance operations 
the delaware law opens up a whole host of issues about safety 
and soundness and the appropriateness of extending the federal 
safety net to banks that engage in new or nontraditional 
activities like insurance underwriting seidman said 
we started to consider these issues a few years ago 
specifically in regard to real estate development and insurance 
underwriting activities i think it is time given recent 
developments to revisit these issues seidman said 
citibank the nations largest bank and chase manhattan corp 
the nations secondlargest both have plans to open insurance 
operations in delaware 
citibank has received approval from ellis office but still 
must receive approval from the state insurance commissioner 
ellis said preliminary talks have begun with chase which must 
become a statechartered bank before it can engage in the insurance 
business 
meanwhile the federal reserve board has yet to act on a request 
from five insurance trade organizations to block citibank from 
selling insurance from its delaware offices 
</TEXT>
