moodys investor services inc is reviewing its 
credit ratings for chrysler corp indicating concern about the 
companys finances an official said today 
fitch investors service inc another new york rating agency 
said chrysler was not under review telephone calls to standard amp 
poors corp officials were not immediately returned this morning 
news of moodys review comes as the nations no 3 automaker 
struggles with declining sales and market share and the loss of key 
executives 
there has been deterioration of their performance in the 
marketplace and competition is making inroads said harold h 
goldberg chairman of moodys corporate rating committee 
he said new minivans and sportutility vehicles other automakers 
are beginning to sell are pointed directly at chryslers popular 
dodge and plymouth minivans and jeeps much of chryslers profit 
stems from sales of those vehicles 
chrysler said wednesday it had sold 752935 north americanmade 
cars and trucks through june 10 down 13 percent from the same 
period last year the companys share of the us car market is 
114 percent down from 131 percent a year ago and its portion of 
the truck market dropped to 218 percent this year from 232 
percent last 
goldberg said he expected moodys would decide whether to change 
chryslers baa2 rating by the end of the month the baa2 rating 
reflects a medium level of investmentgrade securities 
chrysler issued a statement calling moodys review 
inappropriate and unwarranted 
chrysler believes that its firstquarter profitability was 
impressive given the massive reduction in dealer inventories and 
points out that the companys 15billion ongoing costcutting 
program contributed substantially to those results the companys 
statement said 
chrysler said it earned 71 million in the first quarter of this 
year down 80 percent from yearago profits in january the 
automakers earnings were dented severely by a big incentive 
program featuring 1000 rebates on dodge caravan and plymouth 
voyager minivans 
big incentive programs and temporary production cuts during 
january by chrysler no 1 general motors corp and no 2 ford 
motor co slashed a huge buildup of unsold new vehicles 
