<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today the government 
may impose severe fines against air polluters even when federal 
officials are slow to decide on proposals for cleaning up the 
atmosphere 
by a 90 vote the justices upheld the enviromental protection 
agencys power to seek fines of up to 25000 a day against a 
general motors plant in massachusetts 
the impact of the ruling for future cases may be limited the 
house and senate have passed separate bills revising the federal 
clean air act that establish new timetables to address the kind of 
problem at issue in the general motors case 
congress is expected to complete action on the legislation this 
year 
todays case involves pollution from car paint at a gm assembly 
plant in framingham mass and focuses on the joint federalstate 
system for cracking down on dirty air 
gm shut down the framingham plant last year in a costcutting 
move 
under the federal clean air act the epa sets national air 
quality standards the states are required to adopt plans to meet 
those standards and submit them to the federal agency 
the epa in 1980 approved a massachusetts plan for reducing 
pollution from paint at auto assembly factories 
the plan required car makers to comply fully with the federal 
rules by dec 31 1985 
but epa officials extended the deadline for any plant switching 
from lacquer paints to enamel which emits less pollutants 
gm initially planned to stay with lacquer at the framingham 
factory but in june 1985 announced it would convert to enamel by 
the summer of 1987 the company asked that it be exempt from the 
dec 31 1985 standards for 20 months 
massachusetts officials approved gms proposal and submitted a 
revised plan to the epa on dec 30 1985 
without waiting for federal approval gm began building a 200 
million plant in framingham to use the enamel system while 
continuing to operate its factory that uses lacquer paint 
epa officials went to federal court in august 1987 seeking fines 
of up to 25000 a day against gm for 20 months of airquality 
violations at the old framingham plant 
it was not until september 1988 that the epa rejected the 
stateapproved pollution control system at the new plant 
a federal judge barred the epa from imposing fines against gm 
for violations of the dec 31 1985 standards the judge said the 
federal agency itself violated the clean air act by taking more 
than four months to rule on the stateapproved plan submitted dec 
30 1985 
but the 1st us circuit court of appeals in 1988 said the epas 
failure to meet the fourmonth deadline does not disqualify it from 
fining companies that violate previously approved pollution control 
rules 
the appeals court ordered further lower court hearings to decide 
the size of the fines 
the supreme court today upheld the appeals court ruling 
justice harry a blackmun writing for the court said 
references to the fourmonth deadline in the law do not create a 
general requirement that the epa process all proposed revisions 
in cleanair plans within four months 
passing mention of the fourmonth period cannot be 
inflated into a requirement that the epa process each and every 
proposed revision within four months he said 
the us chamber of commerce siding with gm said a ruling 
favoring the government is an incentive to the epa to delay and 
treat businesses unfairly 
the case is general motors vs us 89369 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

