<TEXT>
by way of introduction 75yearold thomas f 
fallon sr lifts his knit yellowshirt to display a scar that cuts 
an arc from near the spine around the rib cage to the center of the 
chest 
the mark of surgery in 1981 along with smaller scars from tubes 
inserted into his body for a month are among the more visible 
reminders of the penalty for nearly 50 years of working with 
cancercausing asbestos 
fallons wife josephine says he used to be a big irishman 
now he struggles to lift himself from a chair breathes heavily and 
tires easily whether on the short walk to the corner store to buy 
the daily news or while painting the kitchen doorframe 
asbestos encased the boilers that fallon built and repaired 
throughout his career it tumbled in chunks from ceiling pipes at 
the brooklyn navy yard in the 1950s workers often cut blankets 
from rolls of asbestos to protect themselves from heat 
we used to lay on it we used to handle it with our bare 
hands fallon says pulling out pictures of ship engine boiler 
rooms technical diagrams faded medical bills and legal 
correspondence 
we never thought it was poison in those days he says 
people were dying they never knew they had it 
fallon has mesothelioma a tumor in the lining of lungs caused 
by inhalation of asbestos particles doctors cut out part of one 
lung lining and subjected him to chemotherapy though they only 
gave him three years to live hes survived 10 
fallon is among tens of thousands of victims of meso which 
along with lung cancer and other lesser ailments are remnants of 
either scientific ignorance or willful negligence by us asbestos 
manufacturers and users 
he also is one of 571 plaintiffs suing manville corps asbestos 
trust fund and other companies that supplied asbestos to the 
brooklyn shipyard where battleships such as the us missouri and 
us iowa were built during world war ii if a settlement fails a 
mass trial is set for the fall 
while lawyers haggle over the price for asbestosrelated 
injuries fallon says he simply wants fair compensation for the 
pain he feels on humid days and the travelfilled retirement he was 
denied 
fallon says he never had fair warning from 1932 when he 
learned to be a boilermaker until retiring in 1980 no one told 
him asbestos could cause diseases that now kill about 10000 people 
annually and disable thousands of others 
like many who handled asbestos in shipyards on construction 
sites in chemical plants and elsewhere fallon believes the makers 
of the insulation and building material and the government 
concealed its hazardous effects 
i hope to get a good settlement because the last 10 years have 
been wasted fallon says i cant go no place i cant do 
nothing we planned to travel we cant go too far as far as 
staten island and back 
the way i feel know i want my life back he says i feel 
lost 
fallon and his 78yearold wife live in bay ridge a 
workingclass neighborhood in the shadows of the verrazanonarrows 
bridge that links brooklyn and staten island where one of their 
two daughters lives 
theirs was a mixed marriage hes irish she italian hes from 
brooklyn shes from the bronx fallon says for a while he swept up 
a bar in the morning repaired boilers during the day and did 
freelance typing with his wife at home at night 
they grew up truly believing in the american dream says 
fallons daughter jo ellen falconello they were betrayed pure 
and simple 
fallon says he never made more than 17000 a year but loved 
his work the fallons still rent a onebedroom apartment in a 
twofamily house where they have lived 20 years for 400 a month 
family pictures adorn the end tables the arm chairs have plastic 
seat covers 
the couple lives on social security payments of 1350 a month 
and despite his illness and her hip surgery and rapid heartbeat 
medical bills havent been devastating the fallons saved about 
20000 in their halfcentury together and use the interest for 
luxuries like gifts for the grandchildren 
fallon in 1986 rejected settlement offers totaling 2500 from 
two companies jury awards in some cases have exceeded 1 million 
but fallon just wants enough to compensate for the suffering and 
maybe help his family 
i expected him to get older but not the way it happened it 
just cut him down his daughter says in a way were very 
lucky we still have my father here the quality of his life isnt 
what it should be but he isnt dead 
</TEXT>
