<DOCNO> AP900614-0243 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the government may fine air polluters even 
when federal officials are slow to decide on proposals for cleaning 
up the atmosphere the supreme court ruled thursday 
the justices voted 90 to uphold a lower court ruling supporting 
the enviromental protection agencys power to seek fines of up to 
25000 a day against a nowclosed general motors corp plant in 
massachusetts 
in a separate decision thursday the court barred manufacturers 
from giving discounts to wholesalers and not to retailers when the 
discounts are unrelated to any savings for the supplier or to the 
wholesalers costs the decision came in a case involving a 135 
million antitrust award texaco inc was ordered to pay 
the future impact of the pollution ruling may be limited the 
house and senate have passed bills revising the federal clean air 
act that set new timetables to address the kind of problem at issue 
in the gm case 
congress is expected to complete action on the legislation this 
year 
the case involved pollution from car paint at a gm assembly 
plant in framingham mass 
under the clean air act the epa sets national air quality 
standards the states are required to adopt plans to meet those 
standards and submit them to the federal agency 
the epa in 1980 approved a massachusetts plan for reducing 
pollution from paint at auto assembly factories 
the plan required car makers to comply fully with the federal 
rules by dec 31 1985 but the epa extended the deadline for 
plants switching from lacquer paints to enamel which emits less 
pollutants 
gm in june 1985 said it would convert to enamel by the summer of 
1987 and sought a 20month exemption from the dec 31 1985 
standards 
massachusetts officials approved gms proposal and submitted a 
revised plan to the epa on dec 30 1985 
without waiting for federal approval gm began building a 200 
million plant in framingham to use the enamel system while 
continuing to operate its factory that uses lacquer paint 
epa officials went to federal court in august 1987 seeking fines 
of up to 25000 a day against gm for 20 months of airquality 
violations at the old framingham plant 
in september 1988 the epa finally rejected the stateapproved 
pollution control system at the new plant 
a federal judge barred the epa from imposing fines against gm 
for violations of the dec 31 1985 standards the judge said the 
epa violated the clean air act by taking more than four months to 
rule on the stateapproved plan submitted dec 30 1985 
but the 1st us circuit court of appeals in 1988 said the epas 
failure to meet the fourmonth deadline did not disqualify it from 
fining companies that violate previously approved pollution control 
rules 
the appeals court ordered further lower court hearings to decide 
the size of the fines 
the supreme court upheld the appeals court ruling 
gm closed the framingham plant last year in a costcutting move 
in the texaco case the court unanimously upheld a 135 million 
antitrust award texaco inc was ordered to pay to 12 service 
stations in the spokane wash area 
justice john paul stevens writing for the court said there was 
no evidence that texacos discounts constituted a reasonable 
reimbursement for the value to texaco of the wholesalers 
marketing functions 
business groups that supported texacos appeal had said a defeat 
for the company could undermine the most common distributional 
arrangement in american business the dual channel system in which 
a manufacturer or supplier sells to wholesalers at discounted 
prices lower than those it charges direct purchasing retailers 
but the court said texacos discounts amounted to illegal price 
discrimination barred by a federal antitrust law the 
robinsonpatman act 
a federal jury ordered texaco to pay 449900 a sum that was 
tripled by the judge to 135 million under the act 
the 12 service station dealers that sued said from 1972 to 1981 
they were placed at an unfair competitive disadvantage because 
texaco supplied gasoline to two spokanearea wholesalers john 
dompier oil co and gull oil co at discounts ranging from 25 
cents to 575 cents per gallon less than texaco charged the 
retailers 
dompier sold the gasoline to other retailers under the texaco 
trademark while gull marketed it under private brand names 
the 12 service stations said they suffered because at least part 
of the discounts were passed on to consumers by competing retailers 
who bought from the dompier and gull 
texaco argued that the discounts were legitimate because they 
were available to all wholesalers who purchased from the oil comany 
giant 
stevens noted there was evidence the services offered by the 
dompier and gull were insubstantial and did not justify the 
discount 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

