<TEXT>
the prospect of automated offhours trading at 
the new york stock exchange has some wall streeters echoing the 
sentiments of bluecollar workers displaced by machinery on the 
assembly line 
stock brokers and tradingfloor specialists said thursday they 
were confident their clients would be better served by trading 
shares through the traditional nyse methods they were skeptical 
that the plan would work using computers rather than people on the 
trading floor to execute trades 
some also wondered whether there is enough business in the 
middle of the night to warrant additional hours for the nyse 
if the restaurant is open all night does that make you any 
hungrier one broker asked 
on the floor of the exchange and during cigarette breaks on a 
wall street sidewalk some exchange workers said they were 
confident customers get better service through socalled 
specialists who bring buyer and seller together 
seeking to emphasize advantages of the current system the 
traders said specialists occassionally reach compromises between 
buyers and sellers that bring the seller a higher price than 
originally sought 
show me a machine that can do that said one broker and 
former specialist who spoke on condition of anonymity 
im doubtful it would work but its a foot in the door for 
computerized trading said a specialist who also asked that his 
name not be used i have the feeling its a trojan horse he 
said adding that an automated system likely would be introduced 
during daytime hours if it is accepted at night 
the plan to expand trading hours was first reported in the new 
york times and later confirmed through sources a nyse spokesman 
would not confirm the report but said the exchange has been 
talking about moving to offhours trading for two years 
sources who were familiar with the plan said the offhours 
trading would eventually lead to three trading sessions through the 
night each stock would be traded once at each session with all 
trades handled at a single price 
the big board hopes afterhours trading would bring back 
business lost to the tokyo and london exchanges 
