<TEXT>
a georgia dairy on thursday introduced a 
cholesterolfree milk product that uses vegetable fat in place of 
animal fat 
officials at mathis dairy touted the new drink as safe for the 
millions of people who cant drink milk because of medically 
restricted diets 
the drink which is not technically milk because it contains no 
milkfat is targeted at a limited market and will cost about 30 
cents more per halfgallon than regular milk dairy officials said 
it is the latest bid by the dairy industry to make its products 
more appealing to healthconscious consumers 
were excited as to what this could mean to the dairy industry 
as a whole said jack mathis dairy vice president 
the product to go on sale around atlanta monday will be 
introduced elsewhere depending on its success mathis said he 
expected other dairies some of which already have lowcholesterol 
milks on the market to develop similar products 
mathis said the new product called mathissunup is a joint 
venture with sun up farms inc a smaller atlanta dairy that 
developed the drink it has been served to 8000 people in taste 
tests over the last six months with overwhelmingly positive 
results he said 
joe dibruno of sun up farms said the technology for making a 
cholesterolfree milk has existed for years but he said his is the 
first one that avoids the watery taste common to skim milks which 
contain a tiny amount of fat and cholesterol 
though mathissunup is believed to be the first 
cholesterolfree milk to hit the market researchers in peoria 
ill reported last year they had developed a concentrated milk 
that is low in fat and free of cholesterol and also uses vegetable 
oils 
dibruno said the new product is made in a manner similar to 
standard lowfat milks whole milk which contains 35 percent 
milkfat is funneled through a clarifier which removes the fat 
but instead of the normal practice of putting back measured amounts 
of milkfat a soybeanbased vegetable fat is mixed in 
the resulting drink which contains 2 percent vegetable fat has 
a texture and taste similar to regular 2 percent lowfat milk it 
has 120 calories per serving same as 2 percent lowfat milk and 
has a similar vitamin content dibruno said 
americans consume about 62 billion gallons of milk a year 
although sales of whole milk have declined sharply since 1971 
according to the agriculture department 
